text_answer.content: While this passage in general is ok, I would not feel comfortable speaking with a student about "transgender" students as referenced in this article. And you KNOW that would come up in the conversation, whether it be a question of "what is transgender" or whether they feel it is singling out that student group. When speaking about student groups that would use peer counseling, can we rewrite that portion of the passage to be a little more "generic" and not touch on topics that would generate an entirely different conversation? As it stands, alot of student groups at any different time could need peer counseling for various reasons. Our job is not to hold a discussion on those reasons, but to help them learn how to read and translate passages. (The suicide and transgender conversations would be very touchy for tutors and these passages don't need to encourage that. Also, students will go home and tell their families about these passages and we don't want to be questioned about why those subjects came up in a tutoring session). Just saying...please consider a revision in that portion of the passage re: why students would need peer counseling and avoid controversial subjects that don't need to be addressed in a tutoring session at Huntington. Also please remove the word transgender from the vocabulary section. Thanks!

text_answer.content: This passage needs to be REWORKED!! There is incorrect information and various inconsistencies that make this a poorly done passage. Mostly it relates to the distances in the atmosphere of regular lightning and sprite lightning. Some places in the passage list the distance in measurement in KM and some places in MILES. (i.e. at the beginning of paragraph 2 states that the mesosphere is 50 miles above the ground. The vocabulary question #3 (which is the sentence that mesosphere correctly answers) states that it's 50-80 KM above the earth. The correct distance is 50-80 KILOMETERS. The vocab question #3 (uses mesosphere for the answer) doesn't match the units stated in the passage. Honestly, students can relate to MILES more than kilometers and perhaps measurements should not be listed  in metric units.  I would check the accuracy of this entire article and rewrite it. Also, there's aLOT of numbers, measurements, etc in here for students to plow through. That makes it more boring and more tedious to read. text_answer.content: The inferencing question needs to be looked at. The answer is listed as B. However, no mention is made of any of the sizes of these instruments. So how would a student be able to infer the relationship between pitch and size if no size was mentioned? Many of these students will not have been exposed to enough instruments, if at all, to bring that knowledge with them. I would suggest we add size of instrument into the passage so students can infer the correct answer. Maybe even  list the size in comparison to something they might be familiar with (i.e. the trumpet is the size of a small lamp while the tuba is the size of a kindergarten student....or something like that).
